    <title>Combined summary - Algorithm Agility for Bitcoin to maintain security in the face of quantum and classic breaks in the signature algorithms</title>
    <updated>2026-02-15T03:52:53.173225+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAEM=y+US1-QRgAXStAZ2tsJiPBeQtm7=_q7LrQdDHR=VAci+vA@mail.gmail.com/T/#m0b08e5cb0ce9fac10eaa236e11df8f3b8d0ebece" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-02-09 14:20:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>In a recent discussion on the Bitcoin Development Mailing List, Matt Corallo addressed potential scenarios related to the advent of Cryptographically Relevant Quantum Computers (CRQCs) and their impact on Bitcoin's security and market value. The discourse reflects upon a hypothetical rapid advancement in quantum computing technology that could dramatically shorten the expected timeline for CRQC development from decades to mere years or even months. Such a scenario raises concerns about the ability of CRQCs to compromise Bitcoin's cryptographic security, enabling the theft of bitcoin through the calculation of private keys in seconds.
Corallo explores the implications of a sudden shift in the security landscape, emphasizing the difference between active and inactive or inaccessible coin holders. Active users are likely to move their coins to new, secure outputs, while those who are deceased, have lost their keys, or have locked their coins in an inaccessible manner face the greatest risk. This situation presents a stark contrast to a more gradual quantum threat emergence, highlighting the challenges in responding to a fast-moving technological threat.
The conversation delves deeper into the philosophical and ethical dimensions of responding to such threats. Corallo points out the difficulty in making preemptive decisions about the security status of outputs without clear knowledge of when and how the quantum threat will materialize. This uncertainty complicates any engineering decisions that might infringe upon private property rights, underscoring the importance of principles over reactive measures.
Furthermore, Corallo addresses the dilemma of what actions should be taken if CRQCs begin to steal bitcoins en masse. He suggests that once coins are held in completely insecure outputs, the ethical boundaries become blurred, likening the situation to coins with easily guessable private keys that are routinely stolen. The discussion raises fundamental questions about the balance between ensuring the safety of the network and adhering to the core principles that underpin Bitcoin, such as the sanctity of private property rights.
This exchange highlights the complex considerations facing the Bitcoin community as it navigates the potential future challenges posed by quantum computing. It underscores the need for a careful, principled approach to enhancing Bitcoin's security without compromising its foundational values, even in the face of potentially disruptive technological advancements.</summary>
